{{COI|date=July 2010}} [[File:Howland Forest canopy.JPG|thumb|300px|View of the Howland Forest canopy from one of the site's research towers.]] The '''Howland Research Forest''' is a {{convert|555|acre|km2|adj=on}} tract of mature [[evergreen forest]] in the [[North Maine Woods]], within [[Penobscot County, Maine|Penobscot County]], central [[Maine]]. It is located west of the town of [[Howland, Maine|Howland]].
==History== The tract is part of the 1.1&nbsp;million acres (4,500&nbsp;km²) of Maine forest sold in 2005 by [[International Paper]] (IP) to the [[Seven Islands Land Company]], a private forest investment management holding company. In 2007, the research forest was purchased by [[Northeast Wilderness Trust]] ensuring its wild and natural state into the future.<ref name="HF web">Howland Forest website: http://www.howlandforest.org/</ref>
The Howland Forest is a founding member of the [[AmeriFlux]] and [[FLUXNET]] research networks.<ref name="HF web" />
==Ecology== The Howland Forest study site is located in a boreal transitional forest of the [[New England/Acadian forests]] ecoregion. The forest is dominated by mixed spruce, hemlock, aspen, and birch stands ranging in age from 45 to 130&nbsp;years. The soils are formed on coarse-loamy granitic basal till.<ref>Woods Hole Research Center: http://www.whrc.org/new_england/Howland_Forest/index.htm</ref>
==Research forest== The tract had previously been designated as a research forest under IP's ownership, attracting researchers from the [[US Forest Service]], the [[University of Maine]], [[NASA]], [[NOAA]], and the [[Woods Hole Research Center]]. Areas of study included [[acid rain]], [[nutrient cycling]], [[soil ecology]], and more recently, forest carbon uptake and loss. The forest has one of the longest records of carbon flux measurement in the world, dating to 1996, providing important information about [[carbon sequestration]] in mature forests.
